<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><listPerson xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><person xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="HAL02" sex="2"><persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><roleName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><forename xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Mary</forename><surname xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Cossley Hall</surname><addName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></persName><birth xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1000"><placeName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Jamaica</placeName></birth><death xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1844"/><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial">Mary Crossley Hall was the sister of Mrs Somerville Wood, with whom she lived. She was devoted 
    to Mrs Wood's daughter (who became Mrs Leicester Stanhope). Halls linked to Wood and to Stanhope 
    are coded as Mary Hall.  It is possible that this might confuse entries for her with those for her brother, 
    Thomas James Hall, b. 5 Dec 1788, who became chief magistrate of  the Bow Steet Police Court - and 
    who prior to that seems to have been  Advocate General of Jamaica 1819. He returned to England and 
    married Agnes Carr. The absence of 'Miss' before 'Hall' does not signify since Godwin does not 
    distinguish his contacts consistently in this way.
    
